    Over 90% of microsuction earwax removal professionals in the UK and Ireland that offer microsuction earwax removal have been trained by us. We're trusted by both professionals and the public
    to take care of your ears.












    Many people are discovering that their local NHS medical centre no longer provides ear syringing, also known as ear irrigation, or has long waiting times. This is undoubtedly due to a
    lack of funding, but the fact that ear syringing is inherently less safe than ear microsuction has also played a role. Many people have been injured as a result of the ear syringing procedure,
    which is why we try not to provide it as a service unless it is absolutely appropriate.



     



    Ear infection, hearing loss, tinnitus, perforation of the ear drum, and further impaction of the ear wax are all possible side effects of ear syringing or irrigation, i.e., the ear wax gets
    pushed even harder against the ear drum. Is it any surprise that people are avoiding walk-in ear syringing in favour of microsuction ear wax removal?



     



    "Going private" is now far less expensive than it was, with many hearing centres now offering it as a service. Our patients have repeatedly told us that the money they paid was well worth it
    for the relief of finally being able to hear properly without waiting for an NHS appointment. Why not bypass the line by "going private"?












